why we need secrets where we have configmap because anyway secret can be decoded easily

1. Granular Access Control (RBAC)You can use Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) to restrict who can see what.ConfigMaps: Usually readable by many users and services within a namespace for general settings.Secrets: You can strictly limit access so only specific Pods or authorized admins can read them.2. Encryption at RestWhile data is "encoded" in the manifest, Kubernetes can be configured to encrypt Secrets at rest in the underlying database (etcd).ConfigMaps: Always stored in plain text in etcd.Secrets: If encryption is enabled, an attacker who steals the database cannot read your passwords without the encryption key.3. Safer Memory HandlingSecrets are often mounted into Pods using a tmpfs (in-memory filesystem).This means the secret never actually hits the node's physical disk, reducing the risk of data being left behind or recovered from a hard drive after a Pod is deleted.4. Visibility and Accidental LeaksTools and commands treat Secrets with more caution to prevent accidental exposure:Logs: kubectl get secrets hides the actual values, showing only metadata, whereas kubectl get configmap shows everything in plain text.Auditing: Security tools often look for "Secret" objects specifically to ensure they aren't being printed to logs or shared incorrectly.
